04-436978f1167a","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"a93899d0-0843-5ecf-92e9-b271d2fc8d26","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"2a3cf512-59ff-576c-9560-44565ac3a9ff","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"bbfe4358-ff9d-5fe7-b9fc-aafa1bf965b4","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"6043633a-ac01-5d95-94c6-343802922275","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"c5d40903-c5aa-53af-9f74-cc0f6ea353f8","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"7cc490a8-0474-5fe7-bc44-9cf3996a4c33","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"5fc15816-0bec-575b-8eb4-67f3ae41909c","slug":"management-of-a-skin-lump","fullItemName":"Management of a skin lump","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 0d345502-25d0-446d-8568-4a40c38583af --><h3>Management of a skin lump</h3><!-- end field 0d345502-25d0-446d-8568-4a40c38583af -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 3a1c3db0-1176-4f4f-9949-1a542409c4c1 --><!-- begin field cfda804b-82ee-4e4f-a585-4ffd885097c9 --><ul><li><strong>If the skin lump has any concerning features </strong>(for example dark or irregular pigmentation, irregular shape, or irregular surface; ulceration, skin fixation, or bleeding):<ul><li>Arrange an urgent referral using a 2-week pathway to an appropriate specialist such as a dermatologist; ear, nose, and throat surgeon; plastic surgeon; or head and neck surgeon, depending on clinical judgement and local service provision. See the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/melanoma-pigmented-lesions/\">Melanoma and pigmented lesions</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/skin-cancers-recognition-referral/\">Skin cancers - recognition and referral</a>, and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-malignant-skin-ulcer/\">Palliative care - malignant skin ulcer</a> for more information.</li></ul></li><li><strong>If a benign lump can be confidently diagnosed </strong>(such as a <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/neck-lump/background-information/causes/#benign-tumours\">lipoma</a> or epidermoid cyst):<ul><li>Reassure the person that no further action is usually needed, unless there is recurrent infection, for example.</li></ul></li><li><strong>If there is suspected skin infection and/or <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/neck-lump/background-information/causes/#skin-infections\">abscess</a>:</strong><ul><li>Arrange antibiotic treatment if appropriate, and consider referral for incision and drainage, depending on clinical judgement. See the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/boils-carbuncles-staphylococcal-carriage/\">Boils, carbuncles, and staphylococcal carriage</a> and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/cellulitis-acute/\">Cellulitis</a> for more information.</li></ul></li><li><strong>If there is uncertainty about the diagnosis or management of a neck lump </strong>that appears to be related to the skin:<ul><li>Arrange referral to an ear, nose, and throat surgeon or maxillofacial surgeon, the urgency depending on clinical judgement.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field cfda804b-82ee-4e4f-a585-4ffd885097c9 --><!-- end item 3a1c3db0-1176-4f4f-9949-1a542409c4c1 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"5431314d-6308-530a-b9d8-d4c8322be7a9","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-745","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 13392162-13c8-4674-94b1-945e20a4026c --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 13392162-13c8-4674-94b1-945e20a4026c -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 7450e895-0b38-4957-8f61-c6bbeac8d5bf --><!-- begin field 5fb44793-fd75-42bc-adb5-7a0895ed17ff --><p>The recommendations on management of neck lumps on the skin are extrapolated from the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) clinical guideline <em>Suspected cancer: recognition and referral</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/neck-lump/references/\">NICE, 2017b</a>], together with expert opinion in review articles on neck lumps in children [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/neck-lump/references/\">Jackson, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/neck-lump/references/\">Smith, 2019</a>] and neck lumps in adults [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/neck-lump/references/\">Tan, 2020</a>]. They are also pragmatic, based on what CKS considers to be safe clinical practice, and are in line with the expert opinion of previous external reviewers of this CKS topic.</p><!-- end field 5fb44793-fd75-42bc-adb5-7a0895ed17ff --><!-- end item 7450e895-0b38-4957-8f61-c6bbeac8d5bf -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}